<!-- APPROACH -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">My Approach</div>
    <h2>I design like an architect and iterate like a <em>teacher.</em></h2>
    <p class="body-text">Every learning product I build starts with the same question: what should a learner be able to do that they couldn't do before? From there, I work backward — identifying the knowledge, skills, and practice opportunities needed to get there.</p>
    <div class="approach-grid">
      <div class="approach-card">
        <h4>Evidence-Based Design</h4>
        <p>My process integrates ADDIE and backward design with cognitive load theory, spaced practice, and retrieval-based learning. Good design isn't intuitive — it's a craft grounded in research.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="approach-card">
        <h4>AI as Accelerator</h4>
        <p>I use AI to speed up assessment iteration, content modernization, gap analysis, and scalable revision cycles — while keeping evidence-based pedagogy at the center. AI speeds the work. Principles determine what's worth building.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="approach-card">
        <h4>Built for Real Learners</h4>
        <p>I don't design for the ideal learner. I design for the full range — diverse backgrounds, varied preparation, real constraints. Accessibility and scalability aren't afterthoughts; they're design requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

